<TITLE> Marty condemns 'wall of silence' over CIA prisons </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 STRASBOURG, France, June 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European governments have built a "wall of silence" in response to charges they were complicit in a CIA programme that included holding terrorist suspects in secret jails, a Swiss investigator said on Wednesday. "State secrecy is unacceptable when there are violations of human rights," Dick Marty told the parliamentary assembly of the Council of Europe, the continent's leading human rights forum. "We came up against a wall of silence on the part of European governments," he added in a debate on a June 8 report in which he accused Poland and Romania of allowing the Central Intelligence Agency to host secret prisons on their soil. Both countries strongly deny the charges, and their parliamentarians lined up to attack Marty in the debate. "It is a far-fetched conspiracy theory spiced up with a generous helping of anti-Americanism," said Polish senator Urszula Gacek, describing the report as a "piece of fiction". Romanian socialist Vasile Ungureanu said Marty's report was "like a film scenario" and called for it to be rejected. Marty said in his report that he had proof of the allegations against Poland and Romania, in the form of detailed circumstantial evidence and interviews with European and US intelligence officials. But the Polish and Romanian deputies said this amounted to no more than hearsay, because none of the officials were named. Marty defended the use of anonymous witnesses, saying his sources needed to be protected because they would face charges of high treason in their countries if their identity were reveal
